  Tool calls: [{'name': 'write_document', 'args': {'content': "## Overview\n\nThe Ai Food Maker system employs a scalable, event-driven microservices architecture, decoupling the AI recommendation engine from user interaction and data persistence. We leverage Python/ML frameworks and cloud-native serverless compute for elasticity, ensuring rapid iteration and cost-effective scaling from MVP to enterprise readiness.\n\n## 🔄 Inter-Lens Alignment\n\nThe system operates on a clear, tightly coupled flow, ensuring that business goals translate directly into robust technical execution across all domains.\n\n1.  **Business Need:** User requests a personalized recipe based on constraints (ingredients, dietary needs, mood).\n2.  **Application Layer:** The request hits the API Gateway, which validates the input and routes it to the core Recommendation Service (Microservice).\n3.  **Infrastructure Layer:** The Recommendation Service utilizes serverless compute (e.g., AWS Lambda or Google Cloud Functions) for scalable, cost-effective execution, interacting with managed container services for heavy model inference.\n4.  **Data Layer:** The service retrieves relevant recipe metadata from a highly available NoSQL database (for fast retrieval) and uses a dedicated Vector Database for semantic similarity matching against user preferences.\n5.  **Security Gate:** All API traffic is secured via OAuth 2.0/JWT tokens. Data access to user profiles and proprietary model weights is strictly controlled via role-based access control (RBAC). Observability tools (logging, tracing) are integrated at every layer to monitor performance and security events in real-time.\n\n**Cross-Cutting Concerns:**\n*   **Observability:** Centralized logging and tracing (e.g., Prometheus/Grafana) will be implemented across all services to monitor latency and service health.\n*   **Caching:** Aggressive caching will be deployed at the API gateway and data access layers to minimize latency for frequently requested recipes.\n*   **AI Governance:** Strict input validation and output filtering are enforced to prevent malicious or inappropriate generation.\n\n## 🛠️ Architectural Trade-offs\n\nSuccessful scaling requires deliberate architectural choices that balance speed-to-market with long-term operational cost and complexity.\n\n1.  **Decision | Chosen Path | Reason**\n    *   **ML Deployment | Containerized Microservices | Reason:** Chosen over monolithic deployment to ensure independent scaling of the resource-intensive AI model. This allows us to scale inference capacity independently of the user management service, optimizing cloud spend.\n    *   **Data Persistence | Hybrid (NoSQL + Vector DB) | Reason:** Chosen over a single relational database. NoSQL handles high-volume, structured recipe metadata, while a specialized Vector Database is crucial for achieving high-quality, semantic recommendations based on complex, unstructured user prompts.\n    *   **Compute Strategy | Serverless First (Lambda/Functions) | Reason:** Chosen over persistent VMs or Kubernetes clusters for the MVP. This minimizes operational overhead and cost during low-traffic periods, prioritizing speed of development and elasticity required for a startup environment.\n\n## 📅 Phase-wise Implementation Roadmap\n\n**Phase 1 (MVP / 0-3 months): Core System Validation**\n*   **Focus:** Core functionality (Basic recipe generation).\n*   **Scope:** Single microservice for basic text-to-recipe generation. Simple REST API. Basic relational database for initial recipe catalog. Minimal, foundational infrastructure setup.\n*   **Goal:** Validate the core ML hypothesis and establish the user interaction flow.\n\n**Phase 2 (Growth / 3-12 months): Scale-out and Hardening**\n*   **Focus:** Scalability, personalization, and resilience.\n*   **Scope:** Full microservices decomposition (User Profile Service, Recommendation Service). Implementation of Vector Database. Robust CI/CD pipelines. Full implementation of centralized logging and basic rate-limiting security measures.\n*   **Goal:** Achieve 10k daily active users and optimize ML model performance via continuous feedback loops.\n\n**Phase 3 (Scale / 12+ months): Enterprise and Optimization**\n*   **Focus:** Multi-region deployment, advanced features, and cost optimization.\n*   **Scope:** Multi-region cloud deployment for disaster recovery and low-latency access. Advanced feature integration (e.g., pantry inventory management). Implementation of advanced A/B testing frameworks for model refinement. Full enterprise security compliance and advanced cost modeling.\n*   **Goal:** Establish the platform as a reliable, high-volume service ready for major business partnerships or enterprise rollout.\n\n## ⚠️ Key Risks & Mitigations\n\n| Risk | Description | Mitigation Strategy |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **ML Model Drift** | The AI model's accuracy degrades over time as user preferences change or new data is introduced. | Implement a robust MLOps pipeline with continuous monitoring. Schedule automated retraining cycles based on performance metrics. |\n| **Data Quality & Bias** | Poorly curated recipe data leads to irrelevant or potentially unsafe food suggestions. | Implement strict data validation gates and human-in-the-loop review for critical recipe updates. |\n| **Latency Bottleneck** | High-volume requests overload the inference service, leading to poor user experience. | Utilize aggressive caching strategies and implement horizontal auto-scaling for the inference microservice. Deploy edge computing solutions where possible. |\n| **Security Exposure** | Vulnerabilities in the API gateway or data access could expose user data or proprietary models. | Mandatory security scanning (SAST/DAST) in the CI/CD pipeline. Strict enforcement of least-privilege access controls (RBAC) across all services."}, 'id': 'AMmaDsr4fJsz7WWqzAMT6WOlAI54EqHi', 'type': 'tool_call'}]
